<br>
I suspect it had more to do with game mechanics, however. Within the constructs of this game system, neutral characters tend to be tolerated to some extent most places, and tend to be tolerant to some extent of everyone. There probably wasn't a way to cleanly insert a new variety of neutral into the default alignment system. Think of how much of the playerbase would have been screaming &quot;unfair&quot; if they had listed Iksars as neutrals, but then coded in all that negative faction? An evil listing is like a &quot;People Don't Like You&quot; sign for dummies.<br>
<br>
Neutral Iksar also might not have even been possible within the limits of the game engine - depends on how they calculate relative starting factions and later faction adjustments. It just may not have been mechanically possible to give the Iksar the isolation they needed for their background without making them an extreme alignment. If that were the case (dunno, just speculating), their worship of Cazic Thule would pretty much dictate it had to be an evil extreme alignment.<br>
<br>
Iksar were an attempt to code a more complex morality into a racial culture than the original game design envisioned (IMHO). It was imperfectly done, but more ambitious than just making them scaly hissing dark elves or xenophobic trolls with a jungle theme tacked on.<br>
